## Chain-triggering two in-app messages in one session

You can trigger an in-app message to send from session start, and then trigger a second in-app message to send after a button is pressed in the first in-app message. To do this, you'll need to build a JavaScript bridge to log a button click event that triggers the second message.

### Considerations

- The trigger for the second message must occur on the device side. The Braze SDK won't pick up custom attribute changes that occur on Braze servers. 
- The default 30-second cooldown between in-app message triggers (a device-side rate limit) must be altered in order to show multiple in-app messages in quick succession. Refer to the relevant documents for iOS, iOS Swift, Android, and Web.

### Logging a button click event to trigger the second message

{% tabs %}
{% tab `logEvent()` %}

Add the following code directly into the first in-app message's composer. This will pass the custom event and trigger the second message.

```java
function logEvent() {
appboyBridge.logCustomEvent("CUSTOM_EVENT_NAME");
appboyBridge.requestImmediateDataFlush();
appboyBridge.closeMessage();
} window.addEventListener('ab.BridgeReady', logStartEvent, false); </script>
```

{% endtab %}
{% Deep linking %}

When the button is clicked, the in-app message begins closing and the deep link is passed to a delegate method within your app. The deep link contains instruction to log the custom event named in the link. The delegate method that handles deep links then nests the code that logs the custom event within a delay.

Here is example code for Swift for iOS:

```swift
/** 
Example deep link URL:
yourapp://customEventTrigger?eventName=event_triggering_next_message
*/

func application(_ application: UIApplication, handleOpen url: URL) -> Bool {
    let absoluteString = url.absoluteString
    let dictionary = URLComponents(string: absoluteString)?.queryItems?.reduce(into:[String: String]()) {
        (result, item) in result[item.name] = item.value
    }
    if absoluteString.contains(customEventTrigger) {
        if let eventName = dictionary?[eventName] as? String {
            DispatchQueue.main.asyncAfter(deadline: .now() + .seconds(1), execute: {
                AppDelegate.braze?.logCustomEvent(name: eventName)
            })
        }
    }
return true
}
```

{% alert important %}
`DispatchQueue` makes sure that the closing animation of the first in-app message finishes before `logCustomEvent` is called, which will prompt the next in-app message to display. In the prior example, the second in-app message will display one second after the click occurs.
{% endalert %}

